      "text": "In German main clauses, the conjugated verb must always be the second element in the sentence. This is known as the V2 (Verb-Second) rule. While in English you can say 'Today I am reading', in German, the verb must stay in the second slot.",
      "title": "The Verb-Second Rule"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you start a sentence with a time expression, an adverb, or any other element instead of the subject, the verb still takes the second position. This forces the subject to move to the third position, right after the verb (e.g., 'Heute trinke ich...' instead of 'Heute ich trinke...').",
      "title": "Verb-Subject Inversion"
    }
